{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505728","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505728"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:34:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:34:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2471"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2471"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.5,0.07,0.1,0,0.33]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2471"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111909"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2471"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2471"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93972"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"152"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2091"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2095"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33430"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36850"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44640"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45656"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111909"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 23-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-day history of burning pain while urinating and increased urinary frequency. She also reports that once she feels an urge to urinate, it becomes very difficult for her to hold the urine. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She is sexually active with multiple partners and uses barrier contraception inconsistently. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is mild suprapubic tenderness but no renal angle tenderness. Urinalysis reveals red blood cells, white blood cells and positive leukocyte esterase. Urinary beta-hCG is negative.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications would be most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nitrofurantoin","Azithromycin","Ceftriaxone","Meropenem","Trimethoprim"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has dysuria (burning sensation while urinating), urinary frequency and urgency (hard to hold the urine), suprapubic tenderness, increased WBCs, and positive leukocyte esterase on urine examination. These findings suggest that the patient has a urinary tract infection (UTI). The absence of systemic symptoms and costovertebral tenderness suggest that the patient is suffering from a lower UTI (i.e. cystitis).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWomen are at increased risk of developing a UTI due to a short urethra. Some 70% of cases of cystitis in non-pregnant women are due to \u003Cem\u003EE. coli\u003C/em\u003E. \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus saprophyticus\u003C/em\u003E is also common in sexually active young women.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUncomplicated UTI in non-pregnant women (negative b-HCG) can be treated without antibiotic therapy. This is because many people will become symptom-free within a week, with only marginal benefit (a few days) by using antibiotics. Antibiotics may cause adverse effects, and their use contributes to antibiotic resistance. If there is a decision to proceed with antibiotic therapy, first-line therapy is now considered \u003Cstrong\u003Enitrofurantoin\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrimethoprim\u003C/strong\u003E is no longer considered first-line due to increasing resistance with rates of resistance among \u003Cem\u003EE. coli\u003C/em\u003E urine isolates being higher than 20%.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAzithromycin\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eceftriaxone\u003C/strong\u003E are given to patients suffering from urethritis due to \u003Cem\u003ENeisseria gonorrhoeae\u003C/em\u003E and/or chlamydia. Urethritis presents with dysuria and urethral discharge. In women, gonorrhoea more commonly causes cervicitis than urethritis. This patient with urinary frequency, urgency, suprapubic tenderness, positive leukocyte esterase, and no urethral discharge has cystitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeropenem\u003C/strong\u003E is a carbapenem and is used in patients infected with highly resistant bacteria. This is not a 1st line therapy for a UTI.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Nitrofurantoin is the drug of choice for the empirical treatment of cystitis in non-pregnant women."],"references":["Abou Heidar NF, Degheili JA, Yacoubian AA, Khauli RB. Management of urinary tract infection in women: A practical approach for everyday practice. Urol Ann. 2019 Oct-Dec;11(4):339-346. doi: 10.4103/UA.UA_104_19. PMID: 31649450; PMCID: PMC6798292","Wilson HL, Daveson K, Mar CBD. Optimal antimicrobial duration for common bacterial infections. Aust Prescr.https://doi.org/10.18773/austprescr.2019.001","Chung A, Arianayagam M, Rashid P. Bacterial cystitis in women. Aust Fam Physician. 2010 May;39(5):295-8.","Urinary Tract Infections (adult): Empirical Treatment Clinical Guideline. SA Health Aug 2022.","Therapeutic Guidelines. Acute cystitis in adults [Internet]. Therapeutic Guidelines. 2025 [cited 2025 May 6]. Available from: https://app-tg-org-au.ap1.proxy.openathens.net/viewTopic?etgAccess=true\u0026guidelinePage=Antibiotic\u0026topicfile=bartonella-infections\u0026guidelinename=auto\u0026sectionId=c_ABG_Acute-cystitis-in-adults_topic_8#c_ABG_Acute-cystitis-in-adults_topic_8"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93972"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2471"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93972","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93972"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-21T14:07:45+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-21T14:10:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2471"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111909"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"